INSERT Articles ( Title, UrlSlug, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId, SiteId, Language ) VALUES ( N'Business 2.0', N'business-2-0', N'Business 2.0 was a monthly magazine that focused on covering the rise of the "New Economy" and emerging trends in technology, business, and finance. Founded by magazine entrepreneur Chris Anderson, Mark Gross, and journalist James Daly, the magazine aimed to provide insights and analysis into the rapidly changing landscape of the business world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'Business 2.0 was first published in July 1998, during the dot-com boom when there was a surge of interest in internet startups, e-commerce, and digital innovation. The magazine captured the excitement and disruption brought about by the internet revolution and sought to chronicle the developments and strategies driving the "New Economy."' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'The magazine quickly gained a dedicated readership with its forward-thinking content and coverage of emerging companies, entrepreneurial success stories, and groundbreaking technologies. It offered in-depth profiles of industry leaders, interviews with innovative entrepreneurs, and analysis of emerging business models.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'Business 2.0 was known for its unique editorial style, blending business reporting with elements of technology, design, and culture. It explored the intersection of business and technology and provided insights into how digital advancements were reshaping industries and creating new opportunities.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'In July 2001, Business 2.0 was acquired by Time Inc., then the publishing division of Time Warner. The acquisition allowed the magazine to reach a broader audience and leverage the resources of a major media company.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + 'During its existence, Business 2.0 remained at the forefront of covering emerging trends a